<DOC><DOCNO> AP890913-0122 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1238EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-ColoWeather     09-13 0270</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Colo Weather,0280</SECOND><HEAD>Snow, Record Cold Stun Denver's Homeless</HEAD><DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A freak snowfall and record cold delightedwinter-wheat farmers, delayed airline passengers and threw Denver'shomeless off guard.   ``The farmers with the dryland winter wheat are just jumping upand down because this'll take them through the whole season,'' saidJoe Baskin of the National Weather Service. ``The ground was dry forplanting. This could double production.''   Denver's 2,600 to 3,200 homeless were unprepared for the 2 inchesof wet snow and high of only 39 degrees Tuesday, and neither werearea shelters. The old record for the lowest high temperature forthe date was 46, set in 1974.   ``We were definitely unprepared. We didn't have a coat to giveout,'' said Roy Chappell, program director for the Salvation Army'sShelter.   The earliest snowfall on record in Denver was Sept. 3, 1961, with4.2 inches.   Travelers at Stapleton International Airport experienced averagedelays of an hour and 45 minutes because of poor visibility, aspokesman reported. The heavy snow downed power lines and causedoutages throughout the Denver area.   Greeley tied the record for its earliest snowfall of the year,set in 1974, said Glen Cobb, meteorologist at the University ofNorthern Colorado.   Weld County, northeast of Denver, got as much as 3 inches ofsnow. Evergreen, in the foothills west of Denver, had six.Strangely, the high temperature in the state was in the mountainhamlet of Glenwood Springs, with 71.   Forecasters said the Arctic cold front would start moving outslowly today, and temperatures were expected to reach the 70s and80s by the weekend.</TEXT></DOC>